400 million euros for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit-limit agreements worth a total of €400 million to finance infrastructure in the education, transport and environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euros to finance in the Hungarian budget the transport and environmental protection projects, which will be carried out from the grant of the Cohesion Funds, of which the parties had previously signed a loan agreement for a value of 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The €150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of €300 million for this goal of Hungary, on the use of the remaining €150 million will be decided later, at the extension of the loan contract.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the Debrecen University’s innovation and research project.
During the talks they also covered the topic of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that when Hungary finalised with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will again address the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has funded a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth €8.4 billion.
The interest on the credits is adjusted to the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a commission for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of all of Europe is directed to that previously little-mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buy in the even cheaper EU market, which will burn up quickly?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred destination for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly some Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while in the Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also around Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate promoters and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
The capital Sofia can also be attractive, with commercial and office spaces promising a quick recovery of the investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf havens in Europe, thus being a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria also strive to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present, and there are traditionally many Russian customers on Black Sea beaches and ski havens.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups – says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to install here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old homes in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renew them later.
They require good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
Chalet buyers are the second category (Bulgaria in December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group consists of real estate investors who make their purchases with the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital properties is constantly rising, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these have suffered an annual increase of 21 percent.
The rise in property prices significantly exceeds the growth in wages.
Fodor and the six hundred Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at the level of experts will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts after the emissions reduction period, established in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Currently there are lively discussions on the particular between developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach an agreement that, compared to the situation of 1990, by 2020, the emissions of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another big topic of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be run by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Fund for the Environment (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
6 percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Hydrology Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
He stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, with respect to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit to decrease even by 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to undertake commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signing the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to comply with an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent from the period 1985-87, which our country will meet, the Ministry of Environment said in a press release.
It is much that is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed for after 2012.In this case, the reduction commitments assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of Earth’s average temperature could not be prevented, a fact that scientists say would have inconsequential and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British military units on a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British Air Force (RAD) first took advantage of the services of YouTube: special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban, the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are monitored in the Kandahar General Operations Corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the Air Force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defense registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and published videos of actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but according to the Defense Ministry they also serve to present to the public the true goal of the British army’s presence abroad.
This type of propaganda virtually costs nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - but inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
Americans are making a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the recklessly edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, officers speak as much as possible of losses, without presenting however the bloody part of the battles.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the Iraq and Afghanistan battlefields, but the British army has only recently been taking advantage of this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with the free-to-download shooting video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
