The giant strike forces are gathering.
The League Trade Unions and the National Federation of Workers' Commissions will constitute a strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday's strike that will last indefinitely.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday – the day the final vote on the public health law will be held – the unemployment will begin.
This will cause great difficulties in transportation, as railway traffic will be completely stopped and up to 13 a.m. the workers of the Budapest Collective Transportation Company will also be on strike.
On Friday afternoon, the League unions will report on the details of their Monday strike that they will hold jointly with the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions.
There will also be a strike commission of the LIGA and the National Syndicate of Machinists that will coordinate the actions on Monday.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday the participating trade unions will strike indefinitely if an agreement with the government is not reached.
This means that – on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law – they did not report on the end date of the strike started.
If the National Assembly disapproves the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for strike.
Instead, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide on the future.
Based on the National Assembly’s Monday agenda, it’s also possible that the public health bill will only be voted in the early hours of the night, or at least around midnight.
As a result of the strike that will begin on Monday, there will be significant transport difficulties: railways will stop working indefinitely, in the morning a part of Budapest's collective transport may be stopped and more than half of the interurban bus transport of Volan companies.
Simultaneously, in numerous points of the country there will be closure of half of the roads.
Numerous unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some unions have announced their strike for an indefinite period, others for a definite period.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railways and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on the minimum services, although, as Christmas holidays approach, more and more people travel in the trains.
According to information received so far, from the start of the day until 13 o’clock, the workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will be on strike, the Budapest Airports from 7 to 9 o’clock, the LIGA Electrical and Thermal Energy Industry Unions will hold a four-hour strike, the Educators’ Unions called for a 2-hour strike and the Democratic Educators’ Union of 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Medical Association will go on a national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Health and Social Sector Workers’ Union (SDTSSS) that forms part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal on public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that they gradually introduce the new form of calculation of pensions that will enter into force next year.
The third is to ensure, even before 2010, for the case of advanced pensions the possibility that occupations that deserve it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF), which is part of the League Trade Unions, does not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway side lines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country increases the risk for the Hungarian Guard
According to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, established in August this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region from various points of view.
The company's "risk warning" states: in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the biggest political risk is the fact that "with the aggravation of existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsy population of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes may occur."
The main reason for this is that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy is probably the provocation of an event of this character – added the representative of the research institute.
They asserted that all this was due to one of the main faults of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: “The protagonists of public life ceded the public debate of the Gypsy problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could base their political strategy on the discrepancies between Gypsy and Hungarians.”
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict outbreaks – they estimate.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the stability and democratic development of the country".
We are reminded that: from the fall of 2006 the reorganization of the radical and far-right groups of Hungary has received increasing publicity and momentum, and that since the summer of 2007 there have been numerous organizations in the country that define themselves as "associations of national self-defense".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civilian organizations, while they openly proclaim the training of their members for defence - even armed - (civil defence, national defence, defence of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is, the state," they add.
They stated: all this is produced in accordance with the method that attempts to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on the dissatisfaction of society with politics and political parties.
Because highlighting the civil and the form of association in the case of these associations not only serves to avoid the legal problems of legal registration, but is at the same time also a political strategy.
