The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be received through bidding.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send forty billion dollars to bid, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, this is the first time central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step should solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend,” wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group in his report to customers.
“This coordinated action by central banks likely reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks should really be afraid of what awaits them when they decided to take this step,” said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems of accessing loans and will therefore have to lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with different impacts on global growth.
The central banks so decided, after they failed to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, a London interbank rate that is used for borrowing money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to borrow money even when the U.S., Canada, and UK central banks lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
