Climate of Venus may give an idea of the future of Earth
Venus may have once been a suitable place for life, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like a Earth twin than previously observed.
Venus is the nearest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different type of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results from the European Space Agency for the Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, offer an overview of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes due to the climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, says: “It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of Earth, when they are two planets so similar.
“Our new data makes it possible to build a scenario in which Venus started as Earth, possibly with an habitable environment millions of years ago.”
