Venus is the twin brother of Earth.
Despite the fact that its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been proposed until now.The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and turmoil at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
Three decades ago, researchers had the suspicion that rays could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. on Venus the rays quiet from an altitude of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller's famous model of the origin of life, rays caused life on Earth: storms could have provoked reactions in the ocean that, in turn, gave rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it is not so: if there were life there, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface temperatures reign of 500 ° C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘diabolical’ twin of Earth, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main goal of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for the research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles in "Nature", according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more characteristics in common with Earth than we had thought,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds on the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by clouds that revolves faster.
This phenomenon resembles wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet, also called the Dawn Star or Vespertine Star, orbits the Sun for 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars, is not very similar to Earth, scientists rely on the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had clustered that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
