Now, suddenly, Richard Gere is the most important argument for watching the movie “The Hunting Party – When a Hunter Becomes What He Pursues” (Why Today Film Titles Have to Be So Long and Foolish?).
The film has a wonderful presentation for the sight: at the bottom, his role as a war reporter is the presentation of what Richard Gere could do, if fate and the film industry had not been so merciful to him.
“The Hunting Party,” despite this triumph, along with “Moerderischer Frieden” which is the German production and will also be released this week, prove to be just a series of unsuccessful films about the war in the Balkans.
The film "Moerderischer Frieden" can be narrated in a few words: it is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt) who want to save a Serbian from the Kosovo snipers, one of them acts very quickly and that also leads him to fall in love with her.
The meaning of the film is lost by the actions and shootings, although we celebrate that the Serbs are not presented once again as the only culprits.
The film is like the German series "Alarm for Cobra 11" without a highway, but in a situation of war.
In the example of "The Hunting Party" you can investigate, because there really never was a good film about the war in the Balkans.
At another time, with another director and another screenwriter (Richard Shepard in two positions), the story about U.S. wartime reporters going to detect a Serbian war criminal called “Zorro,” could probably be a new “Apocalypse Now.”
Thus, the stories are surprisingly similar: the small teams go twice to the mountain to carry out something that the army cannot do and each time results in a journey of madness.
One reason for the failure of "The Hunting Party" is when at the beginning we are introduced to Simon Hunt, to whom he does not allow to be simply a cynic with heart.
No, the script also predicts a love adventure with a Bosnian Muslim who will kill later.
Then “The Hunting Party” is very far from reality, especially when in the last five minutes the reporters with an impressive speed accomplish what they could not accomplish for five years NATO, the CIA and all the heads-hunting world, which was to capture the war criminal and leave the Bosnian Muslims to avenge in a just way.
It is so bad, that they want to appeal to the international court in The Hague based on the crimes against cinematic logic.
However, the purpose of the film is, in fact, a deeply human one.
The film wants to condemn the fact that Karadzic and Mladić are still free, and highlights that Americans and French are not really concerned about pursuing them, because they have political arrangements between them.
Sometimes the good and the bad are so similar, so one comes to mind a very famous poem of Brecht.
In this poem it is a mask of an Asian demon: "In the big wrinkles on his forehead I see, sharing the feelings with him, how hard it is to be evil."
In movies like “The Hunting Party” there are also these demons but they demonstrate how hard it is to be good.
The problem is not just the genre of war films in the Balkans.
He recently published in a newspaper that all films about Iraq produced in Hollywood are fiascoes.
It can also be added that there has never been a good film about South Africa.
Almost always one rule applies: when a star goes through a crisis region or through the mines, then something like “Rangoon” with Patricia Arguette, “On the Other Side of All Borders” with Angelina Jolie or “Bloody Diamonds” with Leonardo DiCaprio appears.
Possibly all these conflicts occurred in a short space of time.
They have to spend at least decades until Hollywood rolls a good film about the Holocaust, such as The Schindler's List.
Classics such as the works on the war in Vietnam "The Deer Hunter", "Apocalypse Now" or "Full Metal Jackett" in their time were not celebrated unanimously as masterpieces.
Today we may know too much about global conflicts, and that’s why every mass murder (Massenmord) is presented directly on two TVs at home.
And that’s because screenwriters don’t have the slightest restraint (which is necessary to be able to) in telling good stories.
"To be or not to be" or "The Great Dictator" turned out to be so good at the end, because Lubitsch and Chaplin still didn't know how bad the Nazi regime really was.
