They are not wooden boxes.
Whoever connects the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs over Warhol’s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo-Box "type" on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brill-Boxes, the Stockholm Modern Museet museum conducted internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brill-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hultén museum gave to the Modern Museet museum, are fake, and a hundred of the other "Stockholm-type" ones, which are in circulation in the international art market, also result.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that had soap powder cartons "Brillo".
According to Warhol, in the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Museum Moderna Museet hundreds of Brilliance-carton boxes were exhibited.These were not made by Warhol (due to the costs), but were brought directly from the "Brilliance" carton factory.
It was not about works of art, but about examples (which were only a few objects) exposed.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce in Sweden a Bright-box of wood, but they were not exhibited in the Museum Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as original of the "Brill-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions, some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the museum Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden almost one hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him were produced and exposed.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At this time Warhol had already died three years ago.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives at the Modern Museet Museum, investigated six museum-owned bright-boxes and also three Swedish-owned private boxes that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990s copies shows that painting was applied with a roll without directly printing the tight plates.
“These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol’s official Bright-Box list,” says Lars Nittve, the director of the Modern Museet museum and adds that if the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Commission in New York does not come to any conclusion, the Modern Museet will classify these six boxes as the copies/exhibition objects.”
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these “serious accusations” that they are soap powder boxes.
But from that moment on, everything remained in absolute silence.
